  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.5702" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <dateline>St. Germains, Oxford<lb/>Dec. 23. 1879</dateline>
        <opener>Dear Schuchardt,</opener>

        <p>You are greatly mistaken there is nothing to account for your not having heard more from me excepting the fact (for such I fear it is) that I am ever a bad Correspondent. We were greatly pleased with the Keltische Briefen<note
            n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">Vgl. <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.783">Schuchardt (1886)</ref>
            </bibl> und <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.letter.5697">Brief Nr. 19</ref> (vom 8. Dezember 1876).</note> and I think I told you so: if not I meant to have done so. We also last</p>
        <p>Rhys<note n="2" place="foot" type="editorial">Hierbei handelt es sich um die Fortsetzung der Unterschrift von der zweiten Seite des Briefs.</note>
        </p>
        <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>

        <p>last spring or summer saw that you were making a sojourn in the south of Spain: I felt I envied you very much, though it is not Spain I want to visit so much as France and Italy. I should have replied to your last letter sooner but we have been in some trouble about little <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5032">
Myfanwy</persName> as she has been ill but she is <pb
            facs="#IMG.3"
            n="3"/> now getting better. I am sorry to say we have no photo of hers or else I should have been glad to send it you: in lieu thereof I venture to send you one of my own taken at Carnarvon last summer. <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5032">
Myfanwy</persName> has no brother but she has a little sister whose name is <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5033">Olwen</persName>: she is now three years and a half old.</p>
        <pb facs="#IMG.4" n="4"/>
        <p>I do not know much about <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2886">
Trübner</persName>’s arrangements and I am inclined to believe that Zupitza<note
            n="3" place="foot" type="editorial">Vermutlich <persName>

Julius Zupitza</persName> (1844–1895), Germanist und Anglist, seit 1876 Professor für englische Philologie in Berlin. Es geht um die zweite und verbesserte Auflage der "<bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.5864">Lectures on Welsh Philology</ref>
            </bibl>", die 1879 wiederum bei Trübner &amp; Co. erschien; siehe auch den vorhergehenden Brief (<ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.letter.5701">Nr. 23, vom 20. März 1878</ref>).</note> had no copy of the second edition sent him: in fact I think he gave very few copies away for review this time either here or abroad. If he had done otherwise I have no doubt you would have had one.</p>
        <p>Mrs. Rhys unites with me in wishing you a merry Xmas and a happy new year</p>
        <closer>
          <salute>Believe me</salute>
          <lb/>
          <salute>Yours very truly </salute>
          <lb/>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2510">John</persName>
          </signed>
        </closer>
      </div>
